Tibetan Buddhism sometimes adds a fourth vehicle to the traditional three yanas: Hinayana, Mahayana, and Vajrayana. This addition reflects the diverse and inclusive nature of Tibetan Buddhism, which seeks to cater to the varying spiritual capacities and aspirations of practitioners. The incorporation of a fourth vehicle can be seen as a way to emphasize the importance of individualized spiritual paths and the potential for different approaches to lead to enlightenment. It highlights the flexibility and adaptability of Tibetan Buddhism in accommodating a wide range of practices and beliefs, ultimately aiming to guide practitioners towards the common goal of awakening and liberation.
